ial transition, many women in early nineteenth-century Montreal turned to prostitution and brothel-keeping to feed, clothe, protect, and house themselves and their families. Beyond Brutal Passions is a close study of the women who were accused of marketing sex, their economic and social susceptibilities, and the strategies they employed to resist authority and assert their own agency. Referencing newspapers, parish registers, census returns, coroners' reports, city directories, documents of Catholic and Protestant institutions, police books, and court records, Mary Anne Poutanen reveals how these women confronted limited alternatives and how they fought against established authority in the pursuit of their livelihoods. She details these women’s lives not only as prostitutes but also as wives, mothers, sisters, and daughters who reconstructed the bonds of kinship and solidarity. An insightful history of prostitution, Beyond Brutal Passions explores the complicated relationships between women accused of prostitution and the society in which they lived and worked.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aProstitutesxHistoryx19th centuryxQuebec(Province)xMontreal. 0aProstituteszQuébec (Province)zMontréalxHistoryy19th century. 0aProstituteszQuébec (Province)zMontréalxHistoryy19th century. 0aProstitutionxHistoryx19th centuryxQuebec(Province)xMontreal. 0aProstitutionzQuébec (Province)zMontréalxHistoryy19th century. 0aProstitutionzQuébec (Province)zMontréalxHistoryy20th century. 0aProstitutionzQuébec (Province)zMontréalxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Pre-Confederation (to 1867).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311127402708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015z9783111277035